[2] Australia (Queensland) ex Bali
Date: Mon 21 Jul 2008
From: Dr. Jeffrey Hanna
<jeffrey_hanna@health.qld.gov.au>


Since the beginning of May [2008], 4 travellers
from Bali have had dengue confirmed soon after
arrival in north Queensland, Australia. All 4
were probably viraemic whilst in north
Queensland, and all 4 were confirmed as having
dengue serotype 3. This indicates that dengue 3
is currently circulating in destinations
frequented by travellers/tourists in Bali.

The only other importations into north Queensland
from Bali this year were 2 travellers with
confirmed serotype 4 dengue in March [2008].

--
Dr. Jeffrey Hanna
<jeffrey_hanna@health.qld.gov.au>
Public Health Physician
Tropical Population Health Unit
PO Box 1103
Cairns QLD 4870
Australia

[This confirms another example of _Aedes_
mosquito-transmitted viruses in Bali, dengue 3
and 4 in this report and chikungunya (reported in
ProMED post 20080720.2198 of 20 Jul 2008),
underscoring the risk of dissemination of these
viruses in viremic international travelers. There
was a small outbreak of dengue in Townsville and
Thuringowa, Queensland, in March - April 2007
(see ProMED post no. 20070416.1263). ProMED
thanks Dr. Hanna for sharing this information
concerning recent dengue cases originating in
Bali, and would be interested in knowing if there
are _Aedes aegypti_ present in Cairns in numbers
sufficient to present a risk of either dengue or
chikungunya virus transmission there.

A map of Australia showing Queensland can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/australia/australia_pol99.jpg>
and a map of Indonesia showing the location of
Bali immediately east of Java can be accessed at:
<http://www.lonelyplanet.com/maps/asia/indonesia/bali/>.
The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Indonesia can be accessed at:
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=-2.6,120.9,5>. - Mod.TY]

